{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472540"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:00:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1546"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1546"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.03,0.22,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114844"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1546"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96850"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"731"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1642"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48439"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114844"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department following a syncopal episode. She was running with friends when she suddenly collapsed, but spontaneously regained consciousness. This is her first syncopal episode, though her parents report that she sometimes experiences episodes of palpitations. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. There is no family history of unexplained syncope or sudden cardiac death. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her ECG is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis based on the ECG findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome","First degree heart block","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","Left ventricular hypertrophy","Ventricular ectopic beats"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of syncope and palpitations in a young person, combined with the ECG findings of a short PR interval, widened QRS complexes, and delta waves (seen as an upsloping at the beginning of the QRS complex, most clearly in leads V1-V4) is diagnostic of \u003Cstrong\u003EWolff-Parkinson-White syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition involves an accessory electrical pathway between the atria and ventricles that can precipitate re-entrant tachyarrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst degree heart block\u003C/strong\u003E shows a prolonged PR interval (\u0026gt;200ms) on ECG, which is the opposite of what is seen here. It rarely causes syncope as conduction still occurs, just with a delay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertrophic cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E can present with syncope and carries a risk of sudden cardiac death. However, its ECG features typically include voltage criteria for left ventricular hypertrophy and deep Q waves in the lateral and inferior leads, not the delta waves seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E is diagnosed on ECG using voltage criteria (S wave depth in V1 + tallest R wave height in V5-V6 \u0026gt;35mm) plus non-voltage criteria such as ST depression or T wave inversion in lateral leads. These features are not present in this ECG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular ectopic beats\u003C/strong\u003E appear as broad QRS complexes (\u0026gt;120ms) occurring earlier than expected in the cardiac cycle, usually followed by a compensatory pause. The ECG shows a consistent pattern without ectopic beats.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome classically presents with palpitations and syncope in young people","ECG characteristics of Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome are short PR interval, delta waves, and widened QRS complexes","Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome carries a small but significant risk of sudden cardiac death and therefore requires prompt recognition and referral"],"references":["Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome. In: The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne Clinical Practice Guidelines [online]. 2020 [updated 2020 Aug; cited 2020 Feb 15]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/WolffParkinsonWhite_Syndrome/","Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m I, \u00d6zer S, Karag\u00f6z T, \u015eahin M, \u00d6zkutlu S, Alehan D, \u00c7eliker A. Clinical and electrophysiological evaluation of pediatric Wolff-Parkinson-White patients. Anatolian journal of cardiology. 2015 Jun;15(6):485. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26006136/","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. In: Life in the Fast Lane [online]. 2020 [updated 2021 Feb 7; cited 2020 Feb 15]. Available at: https://litfl.com/hypertrophic-cardiomyopathy-hcm-ecg-library/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96850"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1546"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22126"}]},"exp